Chapter 4: The Dark Sector: Algebraic Origin of DM and DE
4.1 Dark Matter: The 4th Sterile Majorana Mode
The existence of a Dark Matter (DM) candidate in the Quantum Spectral Standard Model (QSSM) is not an ad hoc addition but an algebraic mandate of the Grand Symmetry.
The \mathbb{Z}_3 cyclic permutation symmetry, which acts on the three known generations of fermions, forces a fourth right-handed Majorana mode per generation within the structure of the finite Dirac operator D_F.
 * Three modes are lifted to high mass scales by the seesaw mechanism, leaving the three observed light active neutrinos (with \Sigma m_\nu = 58.703 \text{ meV}).
 * The remaining fourth mode (the Standard Model-singlet fermion, \xi_{DM}) is protected by a residual Klein four-group symmetry. This mode cannot mix with the visible sector and constitutes the Warm Dark Matter (WDM) candidate.
